 ### The Surveyor
 
-The apparatus that maintains the guild's knowledge of its codexes. When a codex is registered, the Surveyor inspects it — determining what kinds of work are applicable and how each is fulfilled for that specific codex. When a codex changes, the Surveyor updates its records. The guild's ability to seed rigs from commission text depends on the Surveyor's knowledge: without a current survey, the guild cannot reliably turn a patron's words into a working rig.
+The apparatus that decomposes the guild's cartograph nodes — visions, charges, and pieces — into the structural understanding the rest of the guild plans against. When a node is admitted to the cartograph, a registered surveyor walks its content and produces a structural decomposition: child nodes the work breaks into, the relationships between them, the questions a planner needs answered before it can fulfill the node. When a node changes, its surveyor re-runs and updates the decomposition.
 
-The Surveyor's records live in the guildhall, not in the codexes themselves — a survey is the guild's understanding of a codex, not part of the codex's own inscriptions.
+Surveyors are kit-contributable: each surveyor declares which cartograph node shapes it can decompose. The Surveyor apparatus is the substrate that holds the registry, dispatches the right surveyor for each node, and durably records what each one produced. See [architecture/surveying-cascade.md](architecture/surveying-cascade.md) for the cascade contract and the surveyor-registration shape.
 
